<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 9:20<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I288e2b10630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7208c42682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:20.</label.designator><headtext>Excited utterance</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I467c48a07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(2)</cite.query>, <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“A statement relating to a startling event or condition made while the declarant was under the stress of excitement caused by the event or condition”<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/> is admissible as an exception to the hearsay rule.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic54e8fd07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] This statute replaces some ambiguous case law.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic54e8fd17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-serial-number="2038786536" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I467da8327fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Yarber v. State,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic54e8fd27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] the Court of Appeals held admissible under the excited utterance exception the recording of an emergency call made by the other driver involved in a collision. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-serial-number="2040218419" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I467e6b827fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Robbins <page no="312"/>v. State,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic54e8fd37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] a victim&apos;s statement to her niece the morning after she alleged that she had been beaten by the defendant was admissible as an excited utterance even though the beating had ended, as victim was speaking incoherently and the defendant was still present at the location where the statement was made. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Supreme Court further noted that it is not simply the length of time between the event and the statement in determining the exception but the totality of the circumstances.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic54e8fd47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] However, the Court declined to allow evidence of statements made by a defendant to police at the scene of the incident, where the declarant stated he was showing the victim his gun, and where the declarant had previously asked one of the other witnesses to help him because he did not want to go to jail, even though the statements to the police were made moments after the shooting had occurred. <eos/><bos/>The Court reasoned that the declarant&apos;s statement to the other witness showed he was looking for an explanation of the shooting prior to police arriving at the scene.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic54eb6e07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>While a person may show signs of being distraught or confused, and while a court may look at those displays to support the excited utterance exception, a declarant need not express any particular emotion when making the statements, as long as the statements are made while the declarant is under the stress caused by the startling event.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic54eb6e17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic54e8fd07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-serial-number="2003397950" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" w-pinpoint-page="122" ID="I467c6fb17fc011ea988285db8533e975">U.S. v. Alexander, 331 F.3d 116, 122, 61 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 866 (D.C. Cir. 2003)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic54e8fd17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-serial-number="1985108105" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I467d0bf17fc011ea988285db8533e975">Miller v. Keating, 754 F.2d 507, 17 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 723 (3d Cir. 1985)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-serial-number="2003397950" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="I467d0bf67fc011ea988285db8533e975">U.S. v. Alexander, 331 F.3d 116, 61 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 866 (D.C. Cir. 2003)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic54e8fd27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-serial-number="2038786536" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I467df6527fc011ea988285db8533e975">Yarber v. State, 337 Ga. App. 40, 785 S.E.2d 677 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="312"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic54e8fd37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-serial-number="2040218419" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I467eb9a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Robbins v. State, 300 Ga. 387, 793 S.E.2d 62 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic54e8fd47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-serial-number="2041244459" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I467f2ed27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Akintoye v. State, 340 Ga. App. 777, 798 S.E.2d 720 (2017)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic54eb6e07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-serial-number="2044063508" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I467fcb127fc011ea988285db8533e975">Jenkins v. State, 303 Ga. 314, 812 S.E.2d 238 (2018)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic54eb6e17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017179" w-serial-number="2048401660" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I468067517fc011ea988285db8533e975">Blackmon v. State, 829 S.E.2d 75 (Ga. 2019)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para>